byshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Heriz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Herz   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. Compare   Gertz   2.","Germanized or Americanized form of Sorbian <b>Herc</b> (see   Herz   5).","Danish and Swedish: of German origin (see   Herz  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Herz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Fritz, Gerhard, Hans, Helmut, Ilse, Arnd, Egon, Ewald, Heinz, Irmgard.","German: from a personal name derived from a short form of the various ancient Germanic compound names with the first element <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’.","German: nickname for a stout-hearted or kind-hearted individual, from Middle High German <i>herze</i> ‘heart’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have in